collectionDetail.introduction: There’s an art to making happy memories!

experiences.introduction: Who says dates can’t be sweeter? You and your date can learn how to make wagashi, a traditional Japanese sweet, at ABC Cooking Studio. Each class is maxed at four people so you have plenty of support.
experiences.name: ABC Cooking Studio - Central

experiences.introduction: Who says dates can’t be sweeter? You and your date can learn how to make wagashi, a traditional Japanese sweet, at ABC Cooking Studio. Each class is maxed at four people so you have plenty of support.

experiences.introduction: Whether you and your partner are beginners or experienced in creating art, try Art Loft’s freestyle painting jam. Each session lasts for 2 hours. All art materials provided!
experiences.name: Art Loft

experiences.introduction: Attend a fun art class at Banana Art Club with your date. Here, art instructions are customised for all ages and abilities. The best part? You can learn together anywhere that’s convenient for you.
experiences.name: Banana Art Club

experiences.introduction: Learn calligraphy at Bonart Workshops and find yourself and your date exchanging beautifully penned love notes later on! Bonart’s copperplate calligraphy workshops include a starter kit.
experiences.name: Bonart Workshops

experiences.introduction: Learn art while enjoying a 270-degree view of Hong Kong’s streets at Choco L'ART Studio. You and your date can bring your own food and drinks free of charge. Sounds like a perfect date.
experiences.name: Choco L'ART Studio

experiences.introduction: Add a fun twist to your date night by learning pottery at Half Corner Studio. Here, beginners can learn clay preparation and hand-building techniques. Regular and floating classes are available.
experiences.name: Half Corner Studio

experiences.introduction: What's sweeter than bringing your date to Lazy Baking Studio to craft confections together? Here, you will be guided through baking, layering, creaming, and adding finishing touches.
experiences.name: Lazy Baking Studio

experiences.introduction: Try something new with your date this weekend by attending Studio 83’s acrylic and oil class. If you need a space for art creation, the studio has DIY painting sessions available.
experiences.name: Studio 83

experiences.introduction: Bake up a little romance by bringing your date at The Little Kitchen Cookery Studio to learn how to create Instagrammable desserts and cakes. You can also learn other savoury dishes here upon request.
experiences.name: The Little Kitchen Cookery Studio

experiences.introduction: Give your date night a different spin by attending Useless Studio’s pottery classes. The studio also offers wheel throwing, ceramic art courses, and other pottery sessions.
experiences.name: Useless Studio

collectionDetail.name: Hong Kong Heritage
collectionDetail.introduction: Explore the historic wonders of Hong Kong!

experiences.introduction: Walk down 170 Yee Kuk Street and get taken back in time with the verandah-type tong lau or tenement found here. The ground floor used to be a frame-maker’s shop while the floors above were residences.
experiences.name: 170 Yee Kuk Street

experiences.introduction: The Jade Market has been in Yau Ma Tei since 1984 after being first built in Guangzhou Street. Developed in the early 1950s by migrated jade merchants, this market is where you can find a huge selection of jade accessories.
experiences.name: Jade Market

experiences.introduction: Kowloon City Walled Park used to be a lawless zone crowded with around 33,000 residents. Demolished in 1993, the walled city was converted into a landscaped park years later.
experiences.name: Kowloon City Walled Park

experiences.introduction: Man Mo Temple is a historic gem dedicated to worshipping Kwan Tai (Martial God) and King-Emperor Man Cheong, the temple still retains its traditional structures even after renovations.
experiences.name: Man Mo Temple

experiences.introduction: Nam Cheong Pawnshop is today’s reminder of the pawnshop industry that once fueled the city’s economy. This shop still carries the symbol of good fortune arriving — an upside-down bat holding a coin.
experiences.name: Nam Cheong Pawnshop

experiences.introduction: Built during the Qing dynasty, Sam Tung Uk used to be a Hakka walled village featuring symmetrical structures. Today, it’s a historical monument with a museum that is open to the public.
experiences.name: Sam Tung Uk Museum

experiences.introduction: Shing Mun War Tunnels is a heritage trail filled with trenches and tunnels from World War II. Here, you can find the remnants of a defensive line built during the war for New Territories and Kowloon.
experiences.name: Shing Mun War Tunnels

experiences.introduction: If you’re in Hong Kong, visit St. John’s Cathedral, Far East’s oldest Anglican Church that survived World War 2. Beside it is the Memorial Cross dedicated to the soldiers killed during the war.
experiences.name: St. John's Cathedral

experiences.introduction: Tai Kwun is Hong Kong’s Centre for Heritage and Arts that used to be a site for 16 historic buildings composed of 3 declared monuments. It has educational exhibitions and programmes you can join in.
experiences.name: Tai Kwun

experiences.introduction: Marvel at the sight of more than 12,000 miniature Buddha statues at Ten Thousand Buddhas Monastery. Let the view of Buddhas with different expressions entertain you as you go towards the main temple.
experiences.name: Ten Thousand Buddhas Monastery

collectionDetail.name: Insta Worthy
collectionDetail.introduction: We did it for the gram.

experiences.introduction: Dragon’s Back offers a beginner-friendly hike with not-so-hilly and easy access to some of the most Insta-worthy views. End your hike by Shek O Village’s beach.
experiences.name: Dragon's Back

experiences.introduction: Choi Hung Estate’s pastel rainbow-coloured offers an Insta-worthy backdrop for your pictures. Find a good spot by the building’s basketball court for your shots!
experiences.name: Choi Hung Estate

experiences.introduction: Western District Public Cargo Working Area offers a nice sunset view and cargo containers as backdrops. The best thing is that this Instagram Pier is just a 10-minute walk from MTR HKU Station.
experiences.name: Western District Public Cargo Working Area
Lok Wah South Estate Car Park

experiences.introduction: Lai Tak Tsuen is an estate known for its helical spring-like interior structure that’s ideal for snapping optical illusion-style shots. The building has 27 floors with 486 units.
experiences.name: Lai Tak Tsuen

experiences.introduction: Snap those perfect “lookup” shots at Ping Shek Estate. Standing in its atrium can make you appreciate its symmetrical and monochromatic design. Lucky you if a plane or bird gets in the frame.
experiences.name: Ping Shek Estate

experiences.introduction: Also known as Monster Building, Yik Cheong Building is a colourful cluster of residential blocks arranged in a grid-like layout. Its gritty look is ideal for a themed Instagram shot.
experiences.name: Yik Cheong Building (Monster Building)

experiences.introduction: Ever since Korean actor Ji Chang-wook did a photoshoot at the mural in Graham Street, visitors have been flocking to this spot to take pictures. Don’t miss out on this bandwagon!
experiences.name: Graham Street

experiences.introduction: Xiqu Centre features a modern approach in its exterior design while depicting grandiosity in the interior. Established in 2019, this building is a world-class performing arts centre.
experiences.name: Xiqu Centre

experiences.introduction: The Mills is where you can take Insta-worthy shots while learning about Hong Kong’s rich industrial history. There’s an experiential retail area where you can meet new and established businesses.
experiences.name: The Mills

experiences.introduction: A vibrant green, Insta-worthy backdrop awaits you at Yuen Long Green Tunnel. A pedestrian subway linking Tai Kei Leng to Yuen Long, it’s lit with yellow light, giving off a surreal and warm effect.
experiences.name: Yuen Long Green Tunnel

collectionDetail.introduction: Hit the streets and check out these masterpieces!

experiences.introduction: Foxglove proves that the best places are hidden in plain sight. This speakeasy presents itself as an umbrella shop on Duddell Street. Go towards the back of the boutique and find the entrance there.
experiences.name: Foxglove
